properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Significant snowfall tonight into Sunday. Total snowfall expected: 15 to 25 cm. Locations: Burin Peninsula, Avalon Peninsula, Clarenville and vicinity, Terra Nova, and Bonavista Peninsula. Time span: until Sunday afternoon. Remarks: Snow will be heavy at times tonight. The snowfall rates will ease by Sunday morning and will end from the south to the north throughout the day. Blowing snow conditions will ease throughout Sunday as the snow ends and the winds gradually shift to northwesterly and begin to weaken. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system will bring significant amounts of rain beginning Monday evening through Tuesday evening over Southern and Central Quebec. Further north, snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres are possible from Monday morning to Tuesday evening in a corridor stretching from Abitibi towards Chaleur Bay, including Quebec City. Snow accompanied by moderate winds may reduce visibilities locally in blowing snow. Freezing rain is likely in the vicinity of the snow-to-rain transition area. A more important episode of freezing rain is also likely for areas of the St. Lawrence Valley between Montreal and Quebec City. Travel could be difficult, especially at rush hour Tuesday morning. There is still much uncertainty about the track of this system and thus about the type and amount of precipitation expected. Please stay tuned for future forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

Description: Blizzard conditions are being reported across the Kivalliq this evening as a deep low pressure system to the east and a strong ridge of high pressure to the west combine to give northwest winds gusting as high as 70 km/h, with widespread poor to near-zero visibilities throughout the region. Blizzard conditions are expected to ease later overnight for Rankin Inlet, Whale Cove and Chesterfield Inlet, but will continue through much of Sunday in Coral Harbour and Naujaat. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. Moist Pacific air in advance of a low pressure system tracking near the international border will spread snow into central Manitoba beginning this evening. Snow, at times heavy, will continue tonight and Sunday as this slowly moving low lingers in the area until Sunday night. General amounts across central Manitoba will be in the 10 to 20 cm range, though the largest snowfall amounts are expected in a narrow band between The Pas and Swan river areas where up to 25 cm will be possible. To the south, the accompanying cold front will move through southern portions of the province tonight and Sunday morning bringing flurries with a risk of freezing rain. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. A cold front moving through southern Saskatchewan this evening is causing freezing rain along it's leading edge. The precipitation may begin as rain in above zero temperatures but quickly changes over to freezing rain as the front moves through and the temperatures drop. The precipitation should turn to snow later this evening and end Sunday by morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. A Pacific weather system is spreading snow across central Saskatchewan tonight. The snow will persist throughout the night, then taper off from west to east on Sunday. Snowfall amounts will likely end up in the 10 to 20 cm range, with up to 25 cm through the Melfort, Nipawin, and Hudson Bay areas. Further south, amounts through tonight and Sunday will be in the 1 to 5 cm range as a cold front swings through, along with a risk of freezing rain or freezing drizzle tonight. Again, the precipitation in southern regions will end from west to east on Sunday. Moderate to strong northeast winds in the areas receiving heavy snow will also give reduced visibilities in blowing snow, especially this evening. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. Moist Pacific air in advance of a low pressure system tracking near the international border will spread snow into central Manitoba beginning this evening. Snow, at times heavy, will continue tonight and Sunday as this slowly moving low lingers in the area until Sunday night. General amounts across central Manitoba will be in the 10 to 20 cm range, though the largest snowfall amounts are expected in a narrow band between The Pas and Swan river areas where up to 25 cm will be possible. To the south, the accompanying cold front will move through southern portions of the province tonight and Sunday morning bringing flurries with a risk of freezing rain. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions are expected tonight in Cape Dorset and on Sunday in Iqaluit as a strong low pressure system crosses southern Baffin Island. Cape Dorset will see blizzard conditions develop later this evening as the low to the east and the high to the west bring northern winds in between gusting up to 80 km/h resulting in near zero visibility in snow and blowing snow. The blizzard should end Sunday morning. Iqaluit will see very strong northwest winds gusting to 90 km/h develop on Sunday as the low pressure system moves to the east. Near zero visibility can be expected in snow and blowing snow. The blizzard should end early Monday morning. Both communities will see wind chill values fall to near -46 during the blizzard. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.
